  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\nL\n=\n\\int_V\n(\\mathbf{r}\\times\\mathbf{J})\n\\,\\mathrm{d}^3x .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Secondary Evolution Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\frac{\\mathrm{d}L}{\\mathrm{d}t}\n=\n\\int_V\n(\\mathbf{J}\\times\\mathbf{B})\n\\,\\mathrm{d}^3x .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $\\mathbf{J}$ denote local current density and $\\mathbf{r}$ the position vector inside a volume $V$.  \nAngular momentum density is generated by the cross product:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\mathbf{r}\\times\\mathbf{J}.\n\\end{equation}\n\nIntegrating this density over the volume gives total angular momentum:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\nL\n=\n\\int_V\n(\\mathbf{r}\\times\\mathbf{J})\n\\,\\mathrm{d}^3x .\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\nIf local electromagnetic interaction drives rotational change, then the torque density is modeled by:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\mathbf{J}\\times\\mathbf{B}.\n\\end{equation}\n\nTherefore,\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\n\\frac{\\mathrm{d}L}{\\mathrm{d}t}\n=\n\\int_V\n(\\mathbf{J}\\times\\mathbf{B})\n\\,\\mathrm{d}^3x .\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nRotation is treated as an emergent accumulated effect of local electromagnetic current and field interactions rather than as a primordial conserved input.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
